NOTES_NUMBERS_1_4 = {
    1: {
        1: 'CONTEXT: The book opens \'in the wilderness\' (bemidbar) -- the Hebrew name for the book. It is the second month of the second year after the Exodus, one month after the tabernacle was erected (Exod 40:17). God speaks from within the completed sanctuary, ordering His people for the march toward the Promised Land. The census is military: Israel is the army of the LORD.',
        2: 'HEBREW: \'Take a census\' is literally \'lift the head\' (se\'u et rosh) -- a phrase that can mean \'to count\' or \'to exalt.\' Each individual matters enough to be counted. In a culture where kings counted armies to display power (cf. David\'s sinful census, 2 Sam 24), this census is commanded by God for a specific purpose: organizing the march toward Canaan.',
        7: 'CHRIST TYPOLOGY: Nahshon the son of Amminadab, leader of Judah, is a direct ancestor of David and of Jesus Christ (Matt 1:4; Luke 3:32-33; Ruth 4:20). Judah leads the march -- the royal tribe from which the Messiah will come. The tribe that camps to the east (toward the sunrise, 2:3) is the tribe that will produce the Sun of Righteousness (Mal 4:2).',
        46: 'THE NUMBER: 603,550 fighting men, consistent with Exodus 38:26. If each man represents a household of 4-5 persons, the total community is roughly 2-2.5 million. This number has been debated extensively. The Hebrew word \'eleph\' can mean \'thousand\' or \'clan/military unit.\' Some scholars read the numbers as tribal military units rather than literal thousands, yielding a total of ~20,000-40,000. The traditional reading takes them at face value.',
        47: 'LEVITE EXEMPTION: The Levites are not counted in the military census because they have a different assignment -- they are God\'s own portion, dedicated to tabernacle service. They belong to YHWH, not to the military. CHRIST TYPOLOGY: As the Levites were set apart from Israel for sacred service, so the church is set apart from the world -- a royal priesthood (1 Pet 2:9).',
        53: 'THEOLOGICAL ARCHITECTURE: The Levites camp around the tabernacle as a buffer zone between the holy presence and the people. Without this buffer, divine \'wrath\' (qetseph) would break out against the congregation. The graduated holiness -- holy of holies > holy place > court > Levite camp > Israelite camp -- structures all of Israel\'s life around the dangerous, glorious presence of God at the center.',
    },
    2: {
        2: 'CAMP LAYOUT: The camp of Israel forms a cross-shaped pattern with the tabernacle at center. Three tribes on each of four sides, Levites as inner ring. God dwells at the center of His people. CHRIST TYPOLOGY: The cross shape of the camp prefigures the cross of Christ, through which God reconciles all things to Himself (Col 1:20). Revelation 21:12-13 describes the New Jerusalem with three gates on each of four sides -- the camp of Numbers 2 made permanent and eternal.',
        3: 'JUDAH FIRST: Judah leads the march and camps to the east -- the place of honor, the direction of the sunrise. Genesis 49:10: \'The scepter shall not depart from Judah.\' The royal tribe leads; the kingly line marches first. From Judah will come David, and from David, Christ the King.',
        17: 'THE ARK AT CENTER: The tent of meeting moves in the middle of the marching order -- God literally marches at the center of His people. He is neither ahead where they cannot keep up nor behind where He might be forgotten, but in their midst. Revelation 21:3: \'The tabernacle of God is among men.\'',
        34: 'OBEDIENCE: The chapter ends with the refrain of Numbers: \'The sons of Israel did according to all that the LORD commanded Moses.\' This refrain will become increasingly ironic as the book progresses and Israel descends into rebellion.',
    },
    3: {
        4: 'NADAB AND ABIHU: Their death for offering \'strange fire\' (esh zarah) is recorded in Leviticus 10:1-3. The phrase means unauthorized, foreign fire -- worship not prescribed by God. The consequences establish that proximity to God\'s holiness demands obedience, not innovation. Their death leaves Eleazar and Ithamar as Aaron\'s surviving sons, through whom the priestly line continues.',
        12: 'FIRSTBORN SUBSTITUTION: God claims every firstborn as His own, based on the Passover (Exod 13:2). The Levites serve as substitutes -- one tribe given to God in place of all the firstborn of all tribes. CHRIST TYPOLOGY: Christ is the ultimate firstborn substitute. He is \'the firstborn of all creation\' (Col 1:15) and \'the firstborn from the dead\' (Col 1:18) who ransoms all the firstborn of God\'s people. The 5-shekel ransom price (v.47) foreshadows the price paid for redemption.',
        13: 'I AM THE LORD: The declaration \'I am the LORD\' (ani YHWH) is the ultimate basis for all commands. God does not argue; He declares. His identity IS His authority. The firstborn belong to Him because He is YHWH -- the self-existent one who struck Egypt and delivered Israel.',
        38: 'MOSES AND AARON AT THE EAST: The highest-ranking camp is before the entrance, to the east. Moses and Aaron guard the entrance to God\'s presence. Any unauthorized person who approaches is put to death. Access to God is mediated, dangerous, and restricted. CHRIST TYPOLOGY: Christ is the new and living way into God\'s presence (Heb 10:19-20), replacing the human mediators with the one Mediator between God and man (1 Tim 2:5).',
        39: 'THE 22,000: The Levite total of 22,000 is 273 fewer than the 22,273 firstborn (v.43), requiring the surplus to be redeemed with silver. Every number matters in God\'s economy. Each life has a specific value and a specific redemption.',
    },
    4: {
        5: 'COVERING THE HOLY OBJECTS: Before the Kohathites can carry the sacred furniture, Aaron and his sons must cover each piece. The ark is covered with three layers: the veil, porpoise skin, then blue cloth. The Kohathites carry the objects but never see them exposed. CHRIST TYPOLOGY: The veil that covers the ark is the same veil that was torn at Christ\'s death (Matt 27:51). What was hidden is now revealed; what was covered is now accessible.',
        15: 'DEATH BY TOUCHING: The Kohathites carry the most holy objects but must not touch them, on pain of death. The tension between service and danger defines Levitical ministry. They are close enough to carry, but too profane to touch. Only the priestly mediation of Aaron and his sons makes this service possible.',
        20: 'NOT EVEN FOR A MOMENT: The Hebrew is emphatic -- the Kohathites must not see the holy objects \'even as they are being swallowed up\' (keva\'la), that is, even for the brief moment of wrapping. The holiness of God is not reduced by familiarity. Those who serve closest to the sacred must maintain the strictest boundaries. CHRIST TYPOLOGY: Under the new covenant, believers are invited to \'come boldly to the throne of grace\' (Heb 4:16) -- an access that would have been fatal under the old covenant.',
    },
}
